  "summary": "Hercule Poirot and Captain Hastings discuss the nature of detective fiction, with Hastings favoring sensational tropes and Poirot arguing that profound crimes are often simple and private. Their conversation is interrupted by a phone call from Inspector Japp, who reports a murder in Andover. Poirot informs Hastings that an elderly tobacconist, Mrs. Asher, has been killed. Although Hastings initially finds the death of a small shopkeeper unexciting, he agrees to accompany Poirot to Andover to examine the anonymous \"ABC\" letter.\n\nIn Andover, Poirot and Hastings meet Inspector Glen. A constable named Dover discovered Mrs. Asher's body in her shop at 1:00 a.m., having been killed by a severe blow to the back of the head. Based on customer sightings, the estimated time of death is between 5:30 and 6:05 a.m. The primary suspect is her estranged husband, Achille Asher, a German alcoholic who had previously threatened her. Inspector Glen notes that nothing was stolen from the shop.\n\nUpon reviewing the anonymous letter, Inspector Glen observes that the handwriting is too clear to have been written by Achille, whose body is paralyzed and prone to shaking. The inspector also notes the high quality of the paper and ink used. Poirot expresses concern regarding a coincidence in the letter, which specifically mentioned the date of the twenty-first.",
